metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #10
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: Orbicular #76
metadata.description:
Generative constellation of planets, a combination of digital and non-digital art.
Created by Pawel Grzelak and Tom Blameworth.

Paint orbs created by Tom, are randomly chosen, placed, rotated, cropped, and shaded.
Various digital elements like cities, planetary rings or background are procedurally generated, and are unique to each edition.


Detailed project breakdown - https://pawelgrzelak.com/orbicular


Press "S" to save 2000px file. This can be slow.

---

Project uses p5.js library.

LICENCE.md included.

metadata.name: Bloc.Plan #96
metadata.description:
Working as an architect and interior designer daily, I always find that creating space is something interesting. Especially a block plan. As an architectural drawing, it serves to inform the viewer of the presence or absence of a space by composing positive and negative spaces on the site. Through this, I found out that block plan can be a captivating visual art as well.

Press [s] to save captured image

created using p5.js
dirbots - Aug22

metadata.name: Asta Collection #123
metadata.description:
In the creation of "Asta," a tapestry of mathematical precision and mythological grandeur unfolds before the viewer. The name itself is an ode to the Old Norse term "Ástríðr," which combines "ás," or the divine, with "fríðr," the beautiful. Much like the gods and goddesses of Norse mythology, "Asta" dwells in a space where disparate forces like unity and fragmentation or chaos and order find harmony.

The visual core of the artwork is composed of concentric circles meticulously shaped from individual spheres. Each circle, akin to the realms over which Norse gods presided, is a universe unto itself, yet all function as part of an overarching cosmic design. The deities of Norse lore were complex beings, embodying both virtues and flaws, and such dualities reverberate through each sphere and orbit within the piece.

Serving as a backdrop for this celestial assembly is a canvas marked by signs of distress and decay. This reflects the concept of entropy inherent in Norse cosmology—often symbolized by the serpent Jormungandr biting its own tail to form a circle. Circles that appear to have lost their center drift aimlessly, reminiscent of gods who have fallen from grace, thereby capturing the unpredictable and imperfect nature of existence.

"Asta" is not merely a visual spectacle; it's an invitation to embark on a philosophical exploration. As viewers traverse the delicate balance between intricate patterns and intentional anomalies, they are compelled to confront the eternal dualities symbolized in Norse mythology—such as order and chaos, the finite and the infinite, and the divine and the mortal.

For those who engage with it, "Asta" serves as more than just an art piece. It becomes a poetic meeting with the sublime and a tribute to the complexities that both life and mythology bestow upon the human experience.

Controls
========
The controls are as follows:
- Press `t` - 370 x 200 png output (thumbnail)
- Press `1` - 650 x 1200 png output
- Press `2` - 1300 x 2400 png output
- Press `3` - 1950 x 3600 png output
- Press `4` - 3250 x 6000 png output
- Press `5` - 5200 x 9600 png output
- Press `6` - 7800 x 14400 png output

Please note that the larger the output, the longer it will take to generate.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #438
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.
